GitHub Copilot: VS Code itself cannot directly allocate or reserve RAM; it uses what your system and OS provide. To maximize available memory for VS Code and its processes:

1. Close unused apps to free up RAM.
2. Set VS Code‚Äôs process priority to ‚ÄúHigh‚Äù in Task Manager.
3. Use a 64-bit version of VS Code.
4. Increase Node.js/TypeScript memory limits if working with large projects (e.g., set `--max-old-space-size=32768` for build tools).

For extensions and tools:
- Make sure you have the latest versions of essential productivity extensions (e.g., Prettier, ESLint, GitHub Copilot, Tailwind CSS IntelliSense, etc.).
- Enable all relevant language servers and AI features.
- Use the ‚ÄúPerformance‚Äù tab in VS Code to monitor resource usage.

If you want a full audit and upgrade of your extensions for maximum productivity, let me know and I‚Äôll list, review, and recommend the best setup for your workflow.

